< Review>
I'm moving away from home for the first time and while spending money gives me major anxiety I wanted to treat myself to a new, comfy, decent sized bed. You know, so I can sleep away the pandemic depression and not get any class work done.
I had been looking online for mattresses, feeling anxious and hopeless, when my mum insisted we go to a store in person (wait, that's a thing?). We ended up at Mattress Firm on Forest Ave, which is basically a nap haven with a large selection of beds to try and choose from. The sales associate, Joshua Dybdahl, was very helpful in finding me a mattress that wouldn't break my back or my bank account (actually it's the most comfortable thing ever and can't wait for it to be delivered).
Josh was also very patient with my mum who indulges in conversation whenever she can (few and far between these days), so as far as I'm concerned he deserves a raise. Or at least... a new mattress?
I left the store feeling confident that I had gotten a great deal, excited to have a queen size memory foam mattress (plus box spring and mattress cover), and grateful that my mum and all her eccentricities had been treated with kindness and charm.

...zZz...< /Review>

<Name>Trevor Thomas<//Name><time>1546624321649< /time><rating>2<//rating>< Text>
I chose two stars rather than one because the gym is extant; if you're already a 24 member, having some gym space available here is better than having none. But on its own terms, this is the worst gym I've ever trained at. The free weight areas are tiny and poorly stocked, with a limited collection of weights, a single worryingly rickety power rack, a single bench, a characteristically worthless Smith machine, and no space to deadlift. The upstairs area has a collection of early-90s Nautilus machines (that, to the gym's credit, does at least include one cable tower, however janky and over-subscribed). There are no showers and extremely limited locker space. But the space is clean, and the staff seems nice, and again: it exists.</Text>

<Review>I'm a member here and it's a little misleading calling it a supersport club because there is no pool or showers. I was told they had to classify the club this way because a major gym just opened on the same block. It has a very relaxed vibe. All the weights, machines and other equipment needed is here. Being classified a supersport club does give you acces to all the other supersport clubs that do have pools in the country. Entry is done through finger scanner and phone number. No cards to get in. The red brick walls feel right and comfortable for the gym. Staff is very friendly and helpful. You have the feeling that the staff knows you and it never feels crowded. It's a comfortable place to get a workout in before or after work. Very large parking garage right next door.</Review>< Name>

The plaque of DI engines, carbon buildup, needed to be addressed. I love my car and I'm very selective in deciding who to trust with working on it. Stealer was a no-go, not only due to an astronomical price tag of $800, but also since quite often the personnel just does not care and would rarely step outside the bulletin instructions. Solution--independent, boutique specialty shops like SSR Performance, who have set their focus on fine work, rather than mass-oriented auto services like oil change and brake pads. While they could gladly provide such basic services for their customers, they focus on fine tuning your vehicle, hence for them it is quality before quantity. That I value more than anything. In addition, their knowledge is beyond that of a car mechanic, since they have a background in engineering, and they also work on development and manufacturing of performance parts and components. After a couple of hours of browsing the Internet at the lounge area of the shop, my car was ready with shiny clean valves, smoother idle, and undeniably improved torque curve with approximately 10% more low- and mid-range torque. I doubt that max. power or max. torque values have significantly changed, but the curve is definitely more enjoyable. < review>
I had the pleasure of working with Shah and Zayn, who worked tirelessly on my 2012 335is. I‚Äôve been to many reputable shops in Southern California such as European Auto Source (EAS), Mod Auto/Mod Bargains, MRF Engineering etc. SSR Performance beats ALL of those shops by a HUGE margin, hands down.

Shah and Zayn even showed up to my home to perform a misfire diagnostic, as well as to install new painted reflectors and didn‚Äôt leave until almost 1am Saturday morning! Talk about dedication and customer service! Who else is willing to go the extra mile like that these days??

While the guys working at those other shops were at home, all cozy in their little beds on a Friday night, Shah and Zayn were up late and resolved my misfire issue, which McKenna BMW incorrectly diagnosed! The problem ended up being a $40 ignition coil whereas McKenna BMW wanted me to perform a $500 walnut blast to cure the misfire!

Shah and Zayn are passionate, extremely capable, have great attention to detail and provide EXCELLENT customer service and follow-up. I was extremely impressed by the level of professionalism and knowledge both of them demonstrated as well as the great advice they gave me for future improvements.

If you are a BMW enthusiast, you know that things in the N54 world are constantly changing. New methods of engine tuning are developed (e.g., MHD) and innovative companies are constantly releasing improved aftermarket parts (e.g., RB Turbo, Pure Turbo, Burger Tuning, VRSF, VTT, etc.) despite the N54 being a mature platform. You want guys like Shah and Zayn, who are up to date with the most current developments, to work on your car.

Things worked on:

-	Misfire and boost leak diagnostic
-	Painted reflectors
-	Fuel-It! E85 fuel lines and ethanol sensor
-	Evolution Racewerks Chargepipe w/Tial BOV
-	Whiteline subframe bushing inserts
-	Walnut blast
-	Oil change
-	BMS Oil Catch Can</review>
